CE 150 Helicopter¶

Introduction¶

This example investigates the performance of moving horizon estimators with different horizons against the measurement noise in a Helicopter Model. We will see how to:

  1. define a Helicopter Model using the Hilo-mpc Toolbox

  2. setup a nonlinear model predictive controller

  3. setup moving horizon estimators with different horizons

  4. simulate with measurement noise in open-loop and closed-loop forms separately

    • open-loop: investigate the estimation performance of MHE with different horizons

    • closed-loop: investigate the influence of MHE with different horizons on the stability and dynamics of the system

Model¶

This example uses a CE 150 Helicopter Model from Humusoft [1]. The helicopter is fixed on a column and has two degrees of freedom. It is a nonlinear system with six states, two outputs and two inputs which are listed in the following table.

\(\phi_y\)
\[deg\]

Table 1: Variables of Helicopter Model

The dynamic equations contains three parts which are given as follows.

* From the equilibrium condition along the pitch axis:

\[\begin{split}\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} J_{\varphi, p} \cdot \ddot{\varphi}_p &= M_1 - M_g - M_{F_{\varphi, p}} - M_{gyro}\\ \text{with}\qquad M_1 &= a_1 \cdot \omega_1^2 \cdot sgn(\omega_1) + b_1 \cdot \omega_1 \\ M_g &= F_g \cdot l \cdot cos(\varphi_p) = K_{Mg}\cdot cos(\varphi_p) \\ M_{F_{\varphi, p}} &= F_{\varphi, p1}\cdot \dot{\varphi}_p + F_{\varphi, p2}\cdot sgn(\dot{\varphi}_p) \\ M_{gyro} &= K_{gyro}\cdot M_1\cdot \dot{\varphi}_y\cdot sin(\varphi_p) \end{aligned} \end{equation}\end{split}\]

The torque \(M_1\) is generated by the thrust of the main rotor 1, and approximated by a second-order polynomial. \(M_g\) is the moment generated by the gravity of the helicopter and depends on the pitch angle \(\varphi_p\) and the distance \(l\) from the center of mass to the rotation axis. \(M_{F_{\varphi, p}}\) is the moment generated by friction which consists of viscous component \(F_{\varphi, p1}\) and Coulombic friction \(F_{\varphi, p2}\).They both depend on pitch angle velocity \(\dot{\varphi}_p\). \(M_{gyro}\) is the moment generated by gyroscope effect that affects on the pitch axis.

* From the equilibrium condition along the yaw axis:

\[\begin{split}\begin{equation} \begin{aligned} J_{\varphi, y} \cdot \ddot{\varphi}_y &= M_2 - M_{F_{\varphi, y}} - M_c\\ \text{with}\qquad M_2 &= a_2 \cdot \omega_2^2 \cdot sgn(\omega_2) + b_2 \cdot \omega_2 \\ M_{F_{\varphi, y}} &= F_{\varphi, y1}\cdot \dot{\varphi}_y + F_{\varphi, y2}\cdot sgn(\dot{\varphi}_y) \\ M_c &= a_v\cdot \omega_1^2 + b_c\cdot \omega_1 \end{aligned} \end{equation}\end{split}\]

The torque \(M_2\) is generated by the thrust of the tail rotor 2 and approximated by a second-order polynomial. \(M_{F_{\varphi, y}}\) is the moment generated by friction which consists of viscous component \(F_{\varphi, y1}\) and Coulombic friction \(F_{\varphi, y2}\).They both depend on pitch angle velocity \(\dot{\varphi}_y\). \(M_c\) is the coupling moment generated by motor 1 that affects on yaw axis.

* From the electrical behavior of the motors

\[\begin{split}\begin{align} T_1\cdot \dot{\omega}_1 &= u_1 - \omega_1\\ T_2\cdot \dot{\omega}_2 &= u_2 - \omega_2 \end{align}\end{split}\]

The relative parameters of the equations above are listed in the following table.

The pitch and yaw angle can be measured in degree. The measurement equations:

\[\begin{split}\begin{align} \phi_p = \varphi_p \cdot 180/\pi\\ \phi_y = \varphi_y \cdot 180/\pi \end{align}\end{split}\]

x = model.set_dynamical_states(['phi_p', 'dphi_p', 'w1', 'phi_y', 'dphi_y', 'w2'],
                                   units=['rad', 'rad/s', 'rad/s', 'rad', 'rad/s', 'rad/s'])
u = model.set_inputs(['U1', 'U2'], units=['V', 'V'])
# p = model.set_parameters(['U1ap', 'U2ap'])
model.set_measurements(['Phi_p', 'Phi_y'], units=['deg', 'deg'])
# model.set_algebraic_states([])

phi_y, dphi_y, w2 = x[3], x[4], x[5]
u1, u2 = u[0], u[1]

# # Constant parameters
T1, a1, b1 = 0.1866, 0.1244, 0.0496
T2, a2, b2 = 0.117, 0.2331, 0.0080

ac = 0.025
bc = -0.0322

J_phi_p = 0.0048
F_phi_p1 = 0.0024
F_phi_p2 = 0.0000103

J_phi_y = 0.0047
F_phi_y1 = 0.0013
F_phi_y2 = 0.000596

k_mg = 0.07088
k_gyro = -0.4

# # Dynamical equations
# for ddphi_p
M1 = a1 * w1**2 * ca.sign(w1) + b1 * w1
Mg = k_mg * ca.cos(phi_p)
#M_F_phi_p = F_phi_p1 * dphi_p + F_phi_p2 * ca.sign(dphi_p)
M_F_phi_p = F_phi_p1 * dphi_p + F_phi_p2 * ca.tanh(50 * dphi_p)
M_gyro = k_gyro * M1 * dphi_y * ca.sin(phi_p)

# for ddphi_y
M2 = a2 * w2**2 * ca.sign(w2) + b2 * w2
#M_F_phi_y = F_phi_y1 * dphi_y + F_phi_y2 * ca.sign(dphi_y)
M_F_phi_y = F_phi_y1 * dphi_y + F_phi_y2 * ca.tanh(50 * dphi_y)
Mc = ac * w1 ** 2 + bc * w1

ddphi_p = (M1 - Mg - M_F_phi_p - M_gyro) / J_phi_p
ddphi_y = (M2 - M_F_phi_y - Mc) / J_phi_y
dw1 = (u1 - w1) / T1
dw2 = (u2 - w2) / T2
dx = [dphi_p, ddphi_p, dw1, dphi_y, ddphi_y, dw2]

# # Algebraic equations (note that it is written in the form rhs = ... ->0)
# rhs = ...

# # Measurement equations
y = [phi_p * (180 / ca.pi), phi_y * (180 / ca.pi)]

# Set measurement equations
model.set_measurement_equations(y)
# Set dynamical equations of the system
model.set_dynamical_equations(dx)

calculating operating points and setting the reference¶

In this part, we need to calculate the operating input according to the given operating state which are regarded as reference and set in the controller.

Condition of operating point: \(\overline{\dot{\varphi}_p} = 0\), \(\overline{u_1} = \overline{\omega_1}\),\(\overline{\dot{\varphi}_y} = 0\), \(\overline{u_2} = \overline{\omega_2}\)

  • From the equilibrium condition along the pitch axis: \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} &\Rightarrow \qquad \overline{M_{F_{\varphi, p}}} = \overline{M_{F_{\varphi, y}}} = \overline{M_{gyro}} = 0\\ &\Rightarrow \qquad 0 = \overline{M_1} - \overline{M_g} = a_1 \cdot \overline{u_1}^2 \cdot sgn(\overline{u_1}) + b_1 \cdot \overline{u_1} - K_{Mg}\cdot cos(\overline{\varphi_p})\\ \end{aligned} \end{equation} \(M_1\) must be positive, so \(\overline{u_1}\) is also positive. Then the solution of \(\overline{u_1}\) is showed as follows: \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \boxed{\overline{u_1} = -\frac{b_1}{2a_1} + \sqrt{(\frac{b_1}{2a_1})^2 + \frac{K_{Mg}}{a_1} \cdot cos(\overline{\varphi_p})}} \end{aligned} \end{equation}

  • From the equilibrium condition along the yaw axis: \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} &\Rightarrow \qquad \overline{M_{F_{\varphi, y}}} = 0 \\ &\Rightarrow \qquad 0 = \overline{M_2} - \overline{M_c} = a_2 \cdot \overline{u_2}^2 \cdot sgn(\overline{u_2}) + b_2 \cdot \overline{u_2} - \overline{M_c}\\ &with \qquad\overline{M_c} = a_c \cdot \overline{u_1}^2 + b_c \cdot \overline{u_1} \end{aligned} \end{equation} Because \(a_c\) is positive and \(b_c\) is negativ, so \(\overline{M_c}\) could be positive or negative.
    If \(\overline{M_c}\) is positive, then \(\overline{M_2}> 0\) because \(\overline{M_2} = \overline{M_c}\). so \(\overline{u_2}> 0\).The solution of \(\overline{u_2}\) can be \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \boxed{\overline{u_2} = -\frac{b_2}{2a_2} + \sqrt{(\frac{b_2}{2a_2})^2 + \frac{\overline{M_c}}{a_2} }} \end{aligned} \end{equation} If \(\overline{M_c}\) is negative, then \(\overline{M_2}< 0\) because \(\overline{M_2} = \overline{M_c}\). so \(\overline{u_2}< 0\).The solution of \(\overline{u_2}\) can be \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \boxed{\overline{u_2} = \frac{b_2}{2a_2} - \sqrt{(\frac{b_2}{2a_2})^2 - \frac{\overline{M_c}}{a_2} }} \end{aligned} \end{equation}
[8]:

def cch_operating_point(phi_p):
    """
    Analytical solution
    calculate the operating point of U (input) according to the states (in this model, only need 'phi_n'.
    :param phi_n: real value or symbolic value in form of casadi.SX
    :return: u1, u2 # or w1, w2: real value or symbolic value in form of casadi.SX
    """

    u1 = -b1/(2*a1) + np.sqrt((b1/(2*a1))**2 + (k_mg*np.cos(phi_p))/a1)
    mc = ac*(u1**2) + bc*u1
    u2 = -b2/(2*a2*np.sign(mc)) + np.sign(mc)*np.sqrt((b2/(2*a2))**2 + mc/(a2*np.sign(mc)))

    return u1, u2  # or w1, w2

#setting the initial condition
dt = 0.05
phi_p0 = 0
phi_y0 = 0
w10, w20 = cch_operating_point(phi_p0)
u0 = [w10, w20]
x0 = [phi_p0, 0, w10,
      phi_y0, 0, w20]  # w0 = u0

model.setup(dt=dt)
model.set_initial_conditions(x0=x0)


pi = np.pi
phi_p_ref = 60 * pi / 180
phi_y_ref = -120 * pi / 180
dphi_p_ref = 0
dphi_y_ref = 0
U1_ref, U2_ref = cch_operating_point(phi_p_ref)
w1_ref = U1_ref
w2_ref = U2_ref
ref_state = [phi_p_ref, dphi_p_ref, w1_ref, phi_y_ref, dphi_y_ref, w2_ref]
ref_input = [U1_ref, U2_ref]

nmpc.quad_stage_cost.add_states(names = ['phi_p', 'dphi_p', 'w1', 'phi_y', 'dphi_y', 'w2'],ref=ref_state,weights = [10, 2, 1, 5, 1, 1])
nmpc.quad_stage_cost.add_inputs(names = ['U1', 'U2'], ref=ref_input, weights=[2,1])
nmpc.quad_terminal_cost.add_states(names = ['phi_p', 'dphi_p', 'w1', 'phi_y', 'dphi_y', 'w2'],ref=ref_state,weights = [10, 2, 1, 5, 1, 1])
nmpc.horizon = 40
pi = np.pi
nmpc.set_box_constraints(
        x_ub=[85 * (pi / 180), 2, 1, pi, 4, 1],
        x_lb=[-85 * (pi / 180), -2, 0, -pi, -4, -1],
        u_ub=[1, 1],
        u_lb=[0, -1],
        y_ub=[85, 180],
        y_lb=[-85, -180],
        z_ub=None, z_lb=None)
nmpc.set_initial_guess(x_guess = x0, u_guess = u0, z_guess = None)
nmpc.setup(options = {'print_level':0})

Moving horizon estimator¶

In this part we setup 6 moving horizon estimators with different horzizons, namely 10, 15, 20, 25, 30 and 40.

Simulation and plotting¶

open loop¶

Here we run a simulation with measurement noise and compare the performance of moving horizon estimators with 5 different horizons(10, 15, 20, 25 and 30). It is noteworthy that the estimator does not participate in the feedback loop. The results of the estimation won’t be input into the controller and it serves solely as an external observer to estimate the state. We input the real value of the state to the controller in order to gurantee the stability of the system.

[11]:

Tf = 20  # Final time
n_steps = int(Tf / dt)
x_est = model.x0
x = model.x0

computation_time_10 = []
computation_time_15 = []
computation_time_20 = []
computation_time_25 = []
computation_time_30 = []
step_time = []

for step in range(n_steps):
    step_time.append(step+1)
    x_est = x
    u = nmpc.optimize(x_est)
    model.simulate(u=u)
    x = model.solution['x:f']
    y_meas = model.solution.make_some_noise('y:f', variance=[2 ** 2, 4 ** 2], mean=[0, 0])[0]

    start_time = time.time()
    mhe_10.add_measurements(y_meas=y_meas, u_meas=u)
    mhe_10.estimate()
    end_time = time.time()
    computation_time_10.append(end_time-start_time)

    start_time = time.time()
    mhe_15.add_measurements(y_meas=y_meas, u_meas=u)
    mhe_15.estimate()
    end_time = time.time()
    computation_time_15.append(end_time-start_time)

    start_time = time.time()
    mhe_20.add_measurements(y_meas=y_meas, u_meas=u)
    mhe_20.estimate()
    end_time = time.time()
    computation_time_20.append(end_time-start_time)

    start_time = time.time()
    mhe_25.add_measurements(y_meas=y_meas, u_meas=u)
    mhe_25.estimate()
    end_time = time.time()
    computation_time_25.append(end_time-start_time)

    start_time = time.time()
    mhe_30.add_measurements(y_meas=y_meas, u_meas=u)
    mhe_30.estimate()
    end_time = time.time()
    computation_time_30.append(end_time-start_time)

After running the simulation we plot the estimated state values from different MHEs and the real state values with the simulation time.

closed loop¶

Here we run a simulation in closed-loop way awhich means that the estimated results from MHEs are used as the input of the controller and investigate the influence of MHEs with different horizons(15, 20, 30 and 40) on the stability of the system.

[5]:

# initialization
model.reset_solution()
nmpc.reset_solution()
mhe_15.reset_solution()
mhe_20.reset_solution()
mhe_30.reset_solution()
mhe_40.reset_solution()

Tf = 20  # Final time
n_steps = int(Tf / dt)
x_est = model.x0
for step in range(n_steps):
    u = nmpc.optimize(x_est)
    model.simulate(u=u)
    x = model.solution['x:f']
    y_meas = model.solution.make_some_noise('y:f', variance=[0.5 ** 2, 1 ** 2], mean=[0, 0])[0]
    mhe_15.add_measurements(y_meas=y_meas, u_meas=u)
    x_est, _ = mhe_15.estimate()
    if x_est is None:
        x_est = x
solution_15 = copy.deepcopy(model.solution)
